  <div id="grooming" class="scroll-mt-40">
    <CaptionedBlock heading="Grooming: Glamour on an Amateur's Schedule" imageAlt="Papillon puppy having its silky coat and ear fringes combed" imageSrc={imgScene3} imagePosition="left">
      <p>Here's the Papillon's best-kept practical secret: all that silk is a single coat with no undercoat, which means light shedding, rare mats, and no mandatory salon schedule. A comb-through 2 to 3 times a week, a little extra attention to the ear fringes and the trousers where tangles start, and an occasional bath keeps a Papillon looking like it has a stylist on retainer.</p>
      <p>The daily ten-second habits are the usual toy-breed pair: a quick eye wipe, and tooth-brushing, which matters for every small jaw. Everything you need to start is in the kit.</p>
    </CaptionedBlock>
  </div>

  <CloudDivider fillClass="fill-[var(--color-mint-100)]" />
  <div id="health" class="scroll-mt-40">
    <CaptionedBlock heading="Papillon Health: What We Check Before You Take One Home" imageAlt="Papillon puppy at a veterinary health check before going home" imageSrc={imgScene4} variant="mid">
      <p>Every Papillon goes home vet-checked, vaccinated, dewormed, and microchipped. Health is a genuine strength: the Papillon is one of the soundest toy breeds, which its 13-to-16-year lifespan reflects. The short list worth knowing: patellar luxation, the standard small-breed kneecap issue; dental crowding, met with the day-one brushing habit; and progressive retinal atrophy in some lines, worth asking about, as with most toy breeds.</p>
      <p>Mind the fine bones while young: no leaping from sofa height, and supervise around bigger dogs. Feeding is simple: your puppy comes with the food it is already eating, and any change should be gradual over a week. See the puppy health checks explained guide.</p>
    </CaptionedBlock>
  </div>
  <CloudDivider fillClass="fill-[var(--color-mint-100)]" flip />

  <CaptionedBlock heading="Your Papillon's First Week at Home" imageAlt="Papillon puppy settling into a set-up playpen during its first week home" imageSrc={imgScene5} imagePosition="left">
    <p>Day 0: we deliver, free, at a time that suits you, usually morning or evening. The playpen, bed, water, and toys are set up before your Papillon explores the room, and we walk you through all 30+ starter-kit items in person. Learn more about how our free home delivery and setup works.</p>
    <p>Days 1 to 3: keep it calm and predictable. A fixed feeding routine, the toilet pads where we placed them, and short, gentle play. Some night whimpering is normal adjustment; Papillons settle fast once the routine reads as safe.</p>
    <p>Days 4 to 7: the routine sticks, and the studying begins; you'll see it watching you work things out. Book your free first lesson with an AVS-certified trainer this week and give that brain its first official job. See what the free AVS-certified training lesson covers.</p>
  </CaptionedBlock>

  <div id="reviews" class="scroll-mt-40">
